result.execSummary:
The defendant Brittany Sholanda Papador was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Negligent Handling of Burning Material, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 941.10(1).
  • Attempt Attempt Disarming a Peace Officer, a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 941.21.
  • Criminal Damage to Property [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse Assessments], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.01(1).
  • Disorderly Conduct [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse Assessments], a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Brittany Sholanda Papador appeared by video, in custody.  Attorney Travis Schwantes appeared by video for Brittany Sholanda Papador.  Attorney Katie Bakunowicz appeared by video for State of Wisconsin. 
Sentencing hearing held. State advised the Court they have complied with the Victims' Rights Law. Statements by each counsel and defendant as to sentencing.

AS TO COUNT 1: Court sentenced the defendant to serve 9 MONTHS in the House of Correction, concurrent, with credit for 207 days served. 

AS TO COUNT 4: Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM term in the Wisconsin State Prison of  2 YEARS AND 6 MONTHS, concurrent to any other sentence, with credit for 207 DAYS time served, the term of INITIAL CONFINEMENT is 1 YEAR, the term of EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 1 YEAR AND 6 MONTHS. 

AS TO COUNT 5: Court sentenced the defendant to serve 9 MONTHS in the House of Correction, concurrent, with credit for 207 days served. 

AS TO COUNT 6: Court sentenced the defendant to serve 90 DAYS in the House of Correction, concurrent, with credit for 207 days served. 

Court STAYED sentences and placed defendant on PROBATION for 3 YEARS.

CONDITIONS OF PROBATION/EXTENDED SUPERVISION
-Complete a course in anger management.
-Mental health evaluation, take all prescribed medications.
-AODA assessment, comply with recommended treatment.
-Absolute sobriety.
-Treatment and/or counseling as determined by agent.
-DV Trauma therapy.
-No contact with D.C.M. and T.D.J. unless approved by the court.
-Obtain/maintain employment/schooling or combination of both.
-No contact with firearms.
-Pay all MANDATORY court costs, fees, and surcharges including: DNA & DV surcharges to be paid during period of probation, if revoked to be paid by defendant's prison funds at a percentage to be determined by the DOC, remainder to be paid during the period of extended supervision; failure to pay will result in a civil judgment subject to any applicable collection procedures. 
-Court WAIVES all non-mandatory court costs, fees, and surcharges due to inability to pay. Any cash bail on deposit to apply and the remaining balance to be returned to the poster.
-Provide DNA Sample.
-DV assessment imposed.

*Court finds defendant is NOT eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program OR the Wisconsin Substance Abuse Program.
*Court advised defendant of right to seek post conviction relief.
*Court advised due to felony conviction the defendant is prohibited from firearm possession, and defendant's voting rights are suspended and may not vote until civil rights are restored.
*Court ordered defendant to sign up for probation no later than 4:00 pm on 9/30/22.
